article.headline: Yellow Jackets not able to stop all the Wildcats
article.linkText: Mahoney picks up slack as No. 5 K-State routs Georgia Tech
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Georgia Tech stopped the player it wanted
to Sunday. It just happened to be the wrong player.

	   The Yellow Jackets held Laurie Koehn, the best 3-point
shooter in the nation last season, to two 3-point goals, but they forgot about
Kansas State's other guard.

	   Megan Mahoney hit four of five 3-pointers for 16 points and had 13
assists to lead No. 5 Kansas State 83-59 Sunday in the second round
of the preseason WNIT.

	   ''I'm very pleased with her balance and she really shot the ball
extremely well today,'' coach Deb Patterson said. ''She walked off
the court with a double-double. She's playing very solid across the
board.''

	   With Mahoney's help, Kansas State made eight of 12 3-pointers and
held the Yellow Jackets to four field goals in the second half. The
victory sets up a semifinal Wednesday in Manhattan with Southern
California, which beat Colorado State 59-58.

	   Georgia Tech coach Agnus Berenato said the plan was to limit
Koehn.

	   ''We held her to two 3s and that's good, but we don't shoot 70
percent from 3,'' the coach said. ''So we can't handle that when a
team shoots that.''

	   Nicole Ohlde had 20 points, Kendra Wecker added 19 and Koehn had
13 for Kansas State. Mahoney shot 6-for-10 from the floor.

	   ''I'm just playing,'' Mahoney said. ''I'm not doing anything
spectacular. My teammates are the ones making buckets.''

	   Sonja Mallory led Georgia Tech (1-1) with 21 points and Fallon
Stokes had 15. Kasha Terry had 11 rebounds.

	   A 7-1 run to start the second half gave Kansas State a 54-44
lead with 16:34 left. Georgia Tech cut the lead to eight, but never
got closer. Wecker and Mahoney made back-to-back 3s and ignited a
13-0 run that gave the Wildcats a 69-48 lead with 10 minutes to go.

	   ''They were playing horse out there,'' Berenato said. ''They're
saying H before it goes up. And then the next one has O.''

	   Kansas State, which led by as many as 25, shot 51 percent in the
first half and made nine of 13 3-pointers in the game. Georgia Tech
outrebounded Kansas State 42-34, but the Wildcats scored 21 points
off Yellow Jacket turnovers. Kansas State held the Yellow Jackets
to 14 percent from the floor.

	   ''It just took playing defense as five instead of one or two,''
Patterson said.

	   Georgia Tech trimmed a 30-21 lead to a point in the first half
after Kasha Terry hit a jumper with 1:10 left to cap a 6-0 stretch.
A 3-pointer by Koehn silenced the rally and the Wildcats took a
47-43 lead at halftime.
